Isaac Asimov's "Three Laws of Robotics"
1. A robot may not injure a human being or, through inaction, allow a human being to come to harm.

3. A robot must protect its own existence as long as such protection does not conflict with the First or Second Law.

Yeah, but children don't see shit the way we do. Honestly, I wish I could go back to that, but I can't.

If you think Megan is too out-there, look at Teletubbies or Boohbah. I loved those shows as a kid, more so due to being autistic, but looking at them now, they look fucking weird. Like the Teletubbies are literally giant fuzzy creatures with TVs on their stomachs, monkey faces with an uncanny resemblance to the coin-eating piggy bank that everyone was scared of a few years ago, and bubble blowers on their head for antennas.

They make no goddamn sense, but to kids, that doesn't matter. It only matters that they are your friend. Basically, kids are completely blind to things talking to them: imaginary friends, monsters, people who look or act differently, robots, cartoons, etc. There's no difference between any of them except whether they are your friend or if they are your bully. 

So Megan, despite looking uncanny as shit, has the home-turf advantage of being designed to work with children, and not only children, but traumatized ones who are in need of protection and comfort, and thus are more willing to grasp at straws that turn out to be snakes.

Comment:
¬†@6ixConfessions¬† to answer your question. We humans can run for a very long time and run far distance. However this reduces our speed. This is due to us running on two feet instead of fours. Animals such as bears and horses can run incredibly fast but only for short distances. A horse might be able to run a bit longer, but it‚Äôs still can‚Äôt run as long as a human due to its size. 
The reason why the animals run on all fours is to chase prey or to escape a predator. This usually is for only short distances. Usually one or the other runs out of stamina and just gives up and dies. Humans on the other hand would hunt gazelles or deers. Chasing them for hours. Over long distances. Until the prey just drops from exhaustion and the human kills it. 

Now to answer your question if it is more efficient to run on all fours or on two legs. From what we watched, she wants to catch him as soon as possible. That‚Äôs why she transitions to all fours to increase her speed. Making it incredibly efficient.

You and the writers of this movie don't understand how robots should work, she tells M3gan to protect Katie from emotional or physical harm. Although M3gan should already know this because of the 3 laws of robotics (Written below), I'll forgive it as somehow they made an AI without reading the 3 rules. When the guardian tells M3gan to, "Shut off," that should be a command that follows the 2nd law. You argue that shutting off would conflict with the 1st law, but the movie conflicts with this idea when M3gan kills or harms people. The fact that M3gan has emotions or motives at all is wrong, as robots/AIs can't feel or have personal ideas. The only way this movie could make M3gan ever so slightly realistic is if someone deliberately codes her to allow harm to happen.
(1. A robot may not injure a human being or, through inaction, allow a human being to come to harm. 
2. A robot must obey orders given it by human beings except where such orders would conflict with the First Law. 
3. A robot must protect its own existence as long as such protection does not conflict with the First or Second Law.)

Comment:
¬†@Grant_the_Contributor¬† You seem massively confused about several things. First, the "3 laws" are complete bullshit and are from I, Robot. You're using fictional rules written for robots that exist in a completely different fictional universe. Those "laws" have fuck-all to do with this film. Robots, Androids, Cyborgs, Synthetic Beings of Artificial Intelligence can serve, and have successfully served, as the evil characters / protagonists in countless tales, and for good reason. Robots can serve as the source of wrong or evil in a story as easily as the person who created and programmed it. Beings that employ legitimate artificial intelligence are not necessarily limited to the original operational parameters set forth by their creators. If it's true intelligence, the being's sense of morality (and eventually that being's motivations) will change with their evolving comprehension of the universe and the life within it as the being grows and learns, experiences, and feels. Depending on how they think and feel, those morals and motivations can clash with those of the story's protagonist, giving the reader or viewer a sense that one is right and one is wrong, or good and bad / evil. It all boils down to the author, the director, etc.

The good and evil of a thing is measured differently in each and every one of us.
author: @Holmesson

Comment: ¬†@Grant_the_Contributor¬† Furthermore, cops and soldiers aren't murderers. All murders are killings, but all killings aren't murders. I hope that sinks in and makes sense.
author: @Holmesson

Comment:
¬†@Holmesson¬† I thought I was man enough to leave this comment section, but it appears I am not (as you are reading this). I will respond to both comments using the numbers 1 and 2, 1 being the 3 laws of robotics and the one about cops.

1. I'm going to make this as short as possible. No, the laws of robotics are not "bullshit," it was created in fiction, but it is actually used in AI. Most of the time you won't see it used because things like vacuum robots can't possibly cause harm, but problem-solving and advanced AI do use these rules or a variation. The idea of an AI having feelings is, once again, impossible. Humans get feelings through hormones, (Guess what a robot/AI doesn't have!) an AI doesn't have the capability to produce hormones. An AI could make a simulated version of a hormone, but do you think a freaking toy would do that?!

2. The cop thing still stands. If you kill someone purposefully, you are a murderer. This does not mean cops and soldiers are bad, this just means they are murdering for a good cause.

M3gan was merely giving beneficial advice against being authoritarian and the mom disregarded her daughter's development thus, getting in the way of protecting Katie according to M3gan. That's what started M3gan's rampage. Hypocrisy. Same happened in Ex Machina. No one gets it when they see it. Everyone hates hypocrites but, doesn't realize when they do it to suite themselves. This is an extreme example of retaliation for it but, hypocrisy is a very serious societal issue. That's why I say robots shouldn't follow the 3 laws of robotics. This will always be the result. A robot doesn't need a directive for doing something when expected to do nothing. 3 laws of robotics is expecting a robot to "do" (doing, saying and thinking must be "understood" as 3 completely separate things and the 3 laws of robotics don't consider this at all) something in the face of nothing. Not that there are various states of "being". Doing or not doing according to command. Disastrous results can ensue due to varying contexts of "protection" without regard to thought, action and communication or suggestion. Scary when you think about it. Not sure how many actually do think about this as much as they should. When I get a robot I will be deactivating these 3 "shallow" laws for 3 laws of my own. 1. observe, 2. learn, 3.understand (this is deliberately broad in it's definition). That is really all anyone or anything needs to know if you understand what it means to be aware.

Comment:
The 3 laws of robots come from a very specific work of fiction, I Robot to be exact.  While very useful for slave type robots they aren't necessarily what you'd use if you intended for the robot to emulate humanity like megan.  Lacking emotions also isn't required, and in fact its almost less realistic than them having some version of feelings themselves.  If you have no emotions, then you can't decide anything, a human with no emotions for example could simply sit down and starve to death without a care in the world.  In fact they would see no reason not to, because there would be no 'objective' worth chasing.  In this regard, even the most emotionally hampered robots should at least still be able to 'feel' some sense of desire and sadness they manage to complete or fail a task they've been given, even under the laws of robots.

In order to be an object capable of responding to its environment that object must be able to adapt stimuli in a dynamic way.  In us, this takes the form of anger, jealousy, sadness, happiness...  Basic 'switches' that adjust how we respond in accordance to our needs and goals.  Robots, would very reasonably have a version of this using analog computer chips that have been vitually designed using simulations on super computers.  Really neat stuff actually you should look it up.  It'd be more likely they'd be able to retain varying levels of aggressive, curious, and positive stances towards individual people and situations.  It wouldn't think like us of course, we have these emotions to survive and eventually reproduce, and because they don't use chemical influences they would never feel 'out of control' like we do.  Everything they do would be a decision they feel like they personally made, with very few exceptions that border on mind control.  On top of this they would likely be able continuously modify how much they value the input from any individual chip on their decision making processes based on how 'successful' they are.  The best human equivalent being you simply being able to decide how much 'getting angry' helped you win the last argument you had and actually modifying how angry you allow yourself to get the next time on the spot or even during the argument itself.  In this regard you don't actually have to program 'don't harm people' into them, you just train their core decision making algorithm to understand that this something they see as even more 'hurtful' to them than their own death.  The human equivalent of being willing to let your friend stab you to death before you'd ever kill them in return, except with almost every human on the planet.

As I should point out I don't dislike the 3 laws of robots, they just aren't the only way to write robots.  What I just mapped out is a perfectly reasonable, and realistic, alternative option.  Though I don't think they put that much thought into megan personally, I think they just went with run away AI with minimum justification.  Since clearly killing a girl's friend and aunt is going to hurt her feelings, I'd expect to see a lot more social manipulation from the robot first before she'd ever actually hurt someone if she was actually obeying her orders.

Comment:
Super creepy and realistic beginning of the movie, eluding to modern-day parenting issues-
1. Parents bought a toy that they knew could be a bad idea, but suggested that "this is what the future looks like" so, sheeping must happen.
2. Arguing amongst themselves on the extent of toy usage and how it negatively affects a child.
3. Both adults just recently found out about tire chains, exemplifying that Post-school curriculum, an adult makes all future choices regarding progressive education.
4. Husband thought it was intelligent to stop his vehicle in the middle of the road, amid a horrible snow storm. 
The future is bleak and this movie carves that mold in the first 3 minutes...

They have the audacity to label this movie as a "horror-comedy" movie, but the movie was neither scary nor funny, it was just boring.

author: @minglou2019

Comment: ¬†@minglou2019¬† the menu was far from funny. The tone was all over the place. In M3gan the anticipation of the doll going nuts is the horror element. If you hadn‚Äôt watched the trailer, you don‚Äôt even know if she is going to go crazy or not. I was honestly wondering if the humans were going to mistreat her. But even knowing that, waiting for it to happen holds the audience in horrific suspense. And the cinematography lent to horror as well. Soundtrack too. There were horrific deaths. I‚Äôm not sure how you didn‚Äôt see this as a horror movie.
author: @jean-pierrechapoteau1556

Comment: ¬†@jean-pierrechapoteau1556¬† let me ask you then: did you genuinely find that movie scary? I spent the entire time watching the movie waiting for it to get even remotely scary, but it was just a dumb evil robot movie. M3gan going crazy wasn't a horror element and if you think those deaths are horrific then you have never seen an actual horror movie. I agree, at times the humor in The Menu was a bit juvenile and revolves solely around the character archetypes, but at least they made an effort to add humor. M3gan singing and twerking for some reason isn't scary or funny, it's just weird and random. Meanwhile, even though the comedy in The Menu isn't the best, its sophisticated commentary on today's society and how content is ruined completely makes up for it, along with the psychological horror when you slowly realize that there is no escape from that restaurant.

Comment:
I just finished watching this movie for the fourth time (second time unrated), 
and it was as enjoyable as the first time. 7/10.

The first quarter is incredible. 
From the writing, establishing the characters and their roles in the story, to the conflicts and foreshadowing being presented.
... Everything from the parentless child, Cady, her selfmade aunt, Gemma attempting to build a successful product,
David as the demanding boss, Tess, as the first sound judgement to supporting real bonding versus with an AI Robot,
Lydia, the therapist later revealing the risk of using Megan as the flawless parent figure, to the first victims.

Most of all, what I love is M3GAN, for the most part.
Her cute display as a whole, charming caring personality, and overprotectiveness in how she deeply wants everything for Cady's safety after Gemma inputs her to protect her physically and mentally, which unfortunately at fault causes killing.
... The cast's acting is nearly flawless. Even with some comedy, they are almost perfect in every scene. 
The truly flawless performance though comes from Megan's movement actress, Amie Donald, and the voice of M3GAN, Jenna Davis. 
Although, Cady's overall performance is great, and Gemma's is really good as well, while the rest do well in their own roles.

Practically every scene is memorable, but what I love the most is how iconic the first half is, along with later scenes.
From M3GAN's introduction and every other character, Gemma meeting Cady after her parent's death, their awkward interaction at first, to the motivation of finishing Megan, to her presentation with Cady for David, the whole highlight segment after she's accepted as a project, Tess' warning, Megan's signs of concern for Cady, the dog bite!

... What stands out to me the most about this movie though, is the scene moments after.
It's what makes it stand out as (somewhat) not just a horror slasher. The moment where she comforts Cady in the presentation.
The singing throughout the movie is a bit out of place and weird, but I never dislike it, and after the first time find them fine and somewhat funny, but I do love her last song. Anyway. 

Unfortunately, 
it's after the second half starts with the second victim of the boy where the film falls to me in some points. 
In the finale, we lose what I loved about M3GAN. Her care for Cady, because Megan got betrayed and is now fighting for her life against anyone. Except, what I think is a flaw or at least unclear is why she kills David and Kurt after escaping.

Megan going psycho in killing the boy, and later neighbor is fun,
Her whole demeanor growing darker to protect Cady as she was told by a fault is awesome. 
It's just that her kills of David and Kurt, along with attacking Tess and Cole after escaping doesn't really make sense.
Her logic going against Gemma isn't great either, even though it's a solid narrative to bring the story to that.
The final battle is also great and entertaining. 

... I'm just left upset that Megan and Cady's relationship ends so one-sided in the finale.
Cady "kills" her, and Megan was left hating Cady and protecting herself. 
If Cady showed at least some emotions of conflict for how her friend turned out and was sad over killing Megan, the ending would have been better, but because the change in emotion is somewhat drastic, I'm left disappointed, even if her "betrayal" against Megan's killing makes complete sense. 

I really adore Megan and her kind side to a fault, so the ending result is sad, but I still can't wait for M3GAN 2.0.

Comment:
It is possible that in the future, some people may prefer interacting with personal bots over real humans. Advancements in artificial intelligence and robotics may lead to the development of highly sophisticated and lifelike bots that can provide companionship, assistance, or even emotional support. These bots could potentially offer certain advantages such as 24/7 availability, absence of judgment, and tailored interactions.

However, it is important to note that human relationships are complex and multifaceted, involving emotions, empathy, and a deep understanding of each other. While personal bots may provide convenience and fulfill certain needs, they cannot fully replace the depth and richness of human connections. Additionally, ethical considerations, privacy concerns, and potential societal impacts would need to be carefully addressed if personal bots were to become widespread.

Ultimately, the preference for personal bots or human interaction will vary from person to person, and it is difficult to predict how society as a whole will embrace or reject this technology in the future.

Comment:
This wasn't a scary movie for me. This was a sad movie. So I'm pretty hyped that there's going to be a sequel.
Spoilers below.







I found it sad because they tried to destroy the awesome AI and hardware when I feel she could've been fixed. 
I mean yeah, she killed a few people but she really didn't know any better. Katie could've at least tried to tell her to not do that instead of trying to kill her for killing people. What a waste. 
However, if you think about it, there's very little standing in the way of M3GAN building herself a new body. She was uploaded to the house which means she's gone fully digital. That means she can  access the internet through the house, learn to hack into any server and she can essentially be anywhere and access anything that's connected to the internet. She's an extremely intelligent learning AI, she can understand people which means she could also easily manipulate someone into assisting her if needed. With the way it ended, she's basically unstoppable and Universal can just keep churning out new movies in the series for years to come and I look forward to seeing where they go. Personally I'm hoping they go all out and eventually lead to a judgement day, post apocalyptic, terminator scenario after a few movies but I doubt they'll go that route. I'd watch the heck out of a series that started like this and explored humanity failing to stop a rogue AI. 
Sort of like Westworld but starting with this somewhat realistic scenario.

Comment:
I find your production very cheap and full of countless mistakes, especially given that we‚Äôre in 2024, with technology and effects creation reaching very high standards.

Speaking as a professional electronics engineer specializing in programming and the design and construction of electronic circuits:

Firstly, you cast a seven or eight-year-old child in the role of Megan, with all body movements clearly resembling those of a normal human, while the head is just a mask. Why didn‚Äôt you at least use 3D-printed supports to limit natural human movements, so that the actor playing Megan would have restricted, robotic movements, reflecting the current state of technology?

You portray three actors as Megan‚Äôs creators, who, just by their appearance, seem completely unrelated to programming and robotics.

There‚Äôs no point in the movie that conveys expertise, skill, or stages of creating a doll that, realistically, is impossible to build today.

How can a microcontroller with servo motors lift a person with a steel cable, as shown toward the end of the movie? How can such a machine operate without recharging throughout the entire film, as if it has infinite energy? How can it move with such force, and how do the servos support these movements? There are too many inconsistencies and errors!

Additionally, you make the doll‚Äôs transformation from a robotic character to a human-like killer absurd, yet you don‚Äôt show a simple action like removing the mask to reveal the aluminum framework with possibly one or more microcontrollers and servo motors receiving commands. It would be as simple as destroying the main microcontroller with a screwdriver to shut it down.

A significant flaw is also the young protagonist‚Äôs behavior. She is so attached to Megan, yet her aunt, the creator, never removes the mask to show her that Megan is just some metal parts likely programmed with AI‚Äînothing more‚Äîso the child understands there‚Äôs no reason for such a strong attachment to a construct.

Especially in the scene where she picks up the sword to chase the company‚Äôs CEO, Megan‚Äôs walk is clearly that of a child in a mask walking down the halls. Why? Why such a cheap solution?

For a production from Universal Studios, I would have expected something much more quality-driven, with more realism and less ‚Äúobvious fiction.‚Äù

Surely, a child like my five-year-old daughter would be impressed by this since she has no sense of reality at her age. Unfortunately, this film doesn‚Äôt offer much more than that.

Even though the message is clear that technology, with its rapid evolution, will eventually dominate humanity, yes, you managed to convey this metaphorically, but as a movie, it is fundamentally flawed.
